This algorithm is designed to handling rate changes.

Dejittering filter will be removed to reduce complexity.
Should have minimal impact in performance.

(Q: Is normalization necessary?)

** May want to run PLL and do time base tracking and adjustment
   even in VBR mode.  Need to recalculate delay on PCR in VBR mode.
   (This is already been done.  Since we will always switch back to
    CBR mode on the 2nd PCR!!)

Move most clock recovery related variable to static variables in pb_clkrec,
instead of in clkrec_info_t.  This should save some memory.

There are two modes of operations: CBR and VBR.


In VBR mode:
  non-PCR TP: out_time = arvl_time + delay
  PCR TP:     out_time = prev_pcr_out_time + pcr_inc


In CBR mode:
  non-PCR TP: out_time = prev_out_time + out_tpi
              (Note: prev_out_time is the out_time, not adj_out_time!)

  PCR TP:     out_time = prev_pcr_out_time + pcr_inc + est_tb_drift
  If out_time <= prev_out_time, adj_out_time = prev_out_time + min_out_tpi


PCR out_time adjustment:
  If out_time <= prev_out_time, adj_out_time = prev_out_time + min_out_tpi
  This should not trigger out timebase adjustment

Buffer violation detection:
  For PCR TP, if out_time cause underflow or overflow,
  adjust out timebase and set discontinuity indicator.
    new_out_time = arvl_time + sys_delay

  For non-PCR TP, buffer underflow or overflow can only happen in CBR mode.
  If out_time cause underflow or overflow, switch to VBR mode.
  
  For VBR mode, non-PCR TP's out_time = arvl_time + delay.
  As long as delay does not cause buffer underflow or overflow,
  the out_time should be fine.


Switch from CBR to VBR mode:
  - when a non-PCR TP has buffer violation
  - when bitrate change is detected on a PCR TP (??)
    (Q: should we only switch to VBR on non_PCR buffer violation?)

  Need to set delay:
    delay = prev_pcr_out_time - prev_pcr_arvl_time


Switch from VBR to CBR mode:
  - when two PCRs are found
      out_tpi = (pcr_inc + est_tb_drift) / pcr_tp_idx_inc

